As an example, consider the case of the performance evaluation of a mutual fund manager who commits to a certain “style,” which can be defined by the set of state variables that are assumed to be of hedging concern (see Sharpe1992; Brown and Goetzmann1997; Pástor and Stambaugh2002a). The mutual fund’s investors will typically have diverse preferences that may lead to greatly different loading constraints. Therefore, using proposition 2, a fair way to evaluate the manager is to take into account the exposure of the managed portfolio to the priced risk factors according to the modified ρ* of the mutual fund. A second application for ρ p and the modified \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} 
